## 3. When to re-open

This DEC reverts to `proposed` if **any one** of the following becomes true:

- LoC exceeds <X> (e.g. 400) **and** decay-adjusted churn exceeds <Y> (e.g. 7) product-driven commits in 90 days.
- A specific feature requires touching > 5 files in this module to land cleanly.
- Cycle count rises above current N (≥ N+1).
- Two or more reviewers / engineers report concrete pain (failing tests, onboarding confusion, PR-comment friction) referencing this file by name.
- A second implementation of the same logic appears in another module (real reuse pressure, not speculative).

Until then: **don't write a PR for this.**

## 4. Note for future-me

The most common reason a healthy file gets re-flagged is metric drift after a format / refactor / merge spike — the same false signal that triggered this DEC. Before opening a successor, re-run the decay-adjusted churn check explicitly:

```bash
git log --since=90.days --oneline -- <path> \
  | grep -vE 'arch-bot|chore\(format\)|chore: strip|^[0-9a-f]+ Merge ' \
  | wc -l
```

If the answer is < 5, the file is still healthy regardless of raw signals.
